ce:section.ce:para:
According to the experimental results, we suggested a plausible mechanism for the photodegradation reaction on the ZnO/BiOBr/C-Dots photocatalyst. As displayed in Fig. 8 , the improved photoactivity of the ternary photocatalyst in visible region is related to two factors. The first factor is up-conversion feature of C-Dots [61]. It means that C-Dots can absorb visible and near-infrared lights and convert them to shorter wavelengths. Thus, C-Dots produce UV photons by up-conversion characteristic, which is necessary to generation of the charge carriers by ZnO, as a wide band gap semiconductor. The second factor is that BiOBr is a narrow band gap (2.88 eV) semiconductor, allowing to more trapping of visible light to generate more charge carriers. According to this description, after excitation of ZnO by up-converted lights with C-Dots, the photogenerated electrons in the CB of ZnO are injected to the less negative CB of BiOBr, while holes are moved from the VB of BiOBr to ZnO. Meanwhile, C-Dots act as electron sinks to trap a part of electrons from ZnO [52]. Therefore, an efficient charge separation occurs via the formed heterojunctions in the ZnO/BiOBr/C-Dots nanocomposite, as confirmed by PL spectra. As seen in Fig. 8, some of the electrons on ZnO and C-Dots react with adsorbed O2 to generate
O2 − radicals as main reactive species. But, the collected electrons in the CB of BiOBr (+0.23 eV/NHE) could not reduce oxygen molecules to superoxide anion radical (−0.33 eV/NHE), whereas, these electrons can convert O2 to H2O2 (+0.695 eV/NHE), owing to proper band position. Subsequently, H2O2 captured electrons to generate
OH, as another major reactive species. Moreover, the oxidation potential of holes in the VB of ZnO (+2.86 eV/NHE) is sufficiently positive to produce OH
by oxidation of OH− and H2O (E0(OH− surf/OH
) = 1.9 V, E0(H2Oads/OH
) = 2.7 V vs. NHE) [62,63].
